metadata.name: Geode #89
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

metadata.name: Harmony #12
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Harmony' is somewhat inspired by the beautiful stain glass window designs of Frank Lloyd Wright (1867-1959).

Each 'Harmony' output is an attempt to find beauty (harmony) within the chaos created by a swirl of colors, shapes, lines and curves.

To download a 1500x2000px PNG:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear.

metadata.name: Tapete #32
metadata.description: This is a generative art piece featuring circles that move and change in response to noise. The movement of the circles is driven by the noise function, creating a dynamic and constantly evolving composition. The appearance and behavior of the circles are influenced by the chosen values of the parameters and variables in the generation process.

metadata.name: Industrial Devolution #40
metadata.description:
As the abandoned sewage planet Xnor lay seemingly dormant, aeons crept by. Erosion and oxidation recombined in plumbing, slowly causing the pipes to evolve sentience and grow to the horizon in a blooming chaos of rust, steel and concrete.

Industrial Devolution is the first long-form generative project using my rayhatching algorithm. It combines a raymarcher for SDFs with a surface orientation based flow field renderer in order to draw arbitrary 3D scenes as line art, with an organic, hatched drawing style. The SDF formulas were generatively designed and parametrized to form ancient landscapes of corroded industrial pipes and immense, ageless blocks of concrete.

The entire code of Industrial Devolution is 3930 characters, using no external libraries.

When done rendering, the output can be right-click saved as an SVG file and plotted using a plotter such as an Axidraw. The lines in the SVG are in random order, so it is recommended to use a path reordering/optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype before plotting. This will greatly reduce the plotting time. The output SVG is intended to be plotted at A3 (297x420mm) using a 0.4mm black pen (but feel free to experiment). You can change this by adding these options to the URL:

  &lw=.4 the linewidth in millimetres
  &d=.8 the line density (multiplier to the line width, density 0.6 recommended for plotter output)
  &h=420 how high the page is, in millimetres (width is always height * 0.707)
  &bg=1 set to 0 to remove background rectangle (bg=0 recommended for plotter output)

Industrial Devolution was released during a live minting event at Bright Moments Gallery, Venice Beach in collaboration with Bright Moments, fx(hash) and Tender.

metadata.name: Phobetor Flora #7
metadata.description: This project imagines the plants of Phobetor which is a super-Earth exoplanet orbiting the pulsar PSR B1257+12 approximately 2,315 light-years away from Earth in the constellation of Virgo.

metadata.name: Zena #128
metadata.description:
Zena is a study of creating complex patterns via manipulating particle angles using math, bitwise operators and noise.

It can take up to a minute to render or longer in low-performance computers. Enjoy the process!

----Best experienced in full screen----

Probabilities;

- 7 different patterns

- 4 frame types

- 2 frame colors

- 4 different particle hues (Rare; full spectrum) 

- Rare; circular placement

- Rare; dark background

You can right click and save as .png (or press 's' in liveMode) once the rendering is done.



Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, September 2022
@distcollective

metadata.name: Metaverse Flora Part 2 #25
metadata.description: This project re-imagines plant life in the metaverse by using L-systems. L-systems were introduced and developed in 1968 by Aristid Lindenmayer, a Hungarian theoretical biologist and botanist at the University of Utrecht. Lindenmayer used L-systems to describe the behaviour of plant cells and to model the growth processes of plant development.

metadata.name: Lineage #192
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: Concrete #369
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Elevation #185
metadata.description:
There’s so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

–

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect’s elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

–

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

–

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: Eyeshadow Roses #33
metadata.description:
"Eyeshadow Roses" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Painterly roses randomly overprinted with heavy streaks of ink. 

The roses grow by a sequence of three spirals, every new spiral smaller and superimposed on the former.  After the roses are fully formed, a random mask of heavy ink is algorithmically screened over the flowers in a pattern of horizontal or vertical lines, occasionally fully flooding the painting. The accumulation of choices evokes graffiti or printmaking. The sequence of choices are interpreted by the computer according to the algorithm. The beauty of these choices are determined by the viewer.

Each piece takes roughly 10 seconds to generate.

Artist: @sarah_ridgley
Press [s] to save the image
JavaScript / p5js | script size: 11kb

metadata.name: Fields of the Abandoned Homeland #74
metadata.description:
This project was started in December 2021. At that time, I didn't know what the result would be. It was only an idea to create something memorable, you know, like a photo that people keep in their wallets, or a picture on someone's office desk, something that evokes warm and nostalgic emotions. I didn't have a specific plan, so I just focused on testing different mechanics that might be useful in my future drop. And then, in February 2022, the war came to my home. For two weeks, my family and I hid from bombs and rockets in the basement of our house, and finally, we were lucky enough to escape. We have been looking for a safe place to stay for months, and with several relocations, depression set in, and it was difficult to believe what was happening. I thought that such events only happened in movies and history textbooks. The only way to distract myself was by coding. And then, during one of our relocations, I realized what should be the main idea of this project. This is what I had watched for hours during every relocation. Whether it was a bus ride or a train ride, only the background changed, but the landscape was almost the same - endless Ukrainian wheat fields. Fields, some of which were occupied, burned, or simply turned into minefields. Fields symbolized by the yellow color on the flag of Ukraine. These are the fields I want to see again but in reverse order, on my way home. 

I dedicate this drop to everyone who, for whatever reason, had to leave their home against their will.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[4] to change resolution
- Press [s] to save

Made with p5js and hope
Copyright @Kitel87 || 2023
